    title: "Psychopharmacology: Receptor Binding & Selection",
    cellular: { title: "Neuroreceptor Pharmacology in Psychotropic Selection", content: "Psychotropic drug selection is guided by understanding which neuroreceptors each agent binds and the clinical consequences of that binding. The major neurotransmitter systems relevant to psychiatric prescribing include serotonin (5-HT, with subtypes 5-HT1A through 5-HT7), dopamine (D1-D5 receptors in mesolimbic, mesocortical, nigrostriatal, and tuberoinfundibular pathways), norepinephrine (alpha-1, alpha-2, beta-adrenergic receptors), histamine (H1 receptors), muscarinic acetylcholine (M1-M5), and gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA-A and GABA-B). Antipsychotics illustrate receptor binding complexity: first-generation antipsychotics (FGAs like haloperidol) are potent D2 antagonists with high affinity, producing effective positive symptom control but also extrapyramidal symptoms (EPS) from nigrostriatal D2 blockade and hyperprolactinemia from tuberoinfundibular D2 blockade. Second-generation antipsychotics (SGAs) have variable receptor profiles — risperidone has strong D2 and 5-HT2A antagonism (still causes EPS and prolactin elevation at higher doses), olanzapine has broad receptor antagonism (D2, 5-HT2A, H1, M1, alpha-1) explaining its efficacy across psychotic and mood symptoms but also its metabolic burden (weight gain from H1 and 5-HT2C blockade, sedation from H1 and M1, orthostasis from alpha-1). Quetiapine has low D2 affinity with high H1 and alpha-1 binding, making it very sedating with less EPS risk; its metabolite norquetiapine inhibits the norepinephrine transporter, providing antidepressant properties. Aripiprazole is a D2 partial agonist — it stabilizes dopamine transmission by acting as a functional agonist in hypodopaminergic states (negative symptoms, mesocortical pathway) and a functional antagonist in hyperdopaminergic states (positive symptoms, mesolimbic pathway), with minimal metabolic effects but risk of akathisia. Clozapine has the broadest receptor profile (D4 > D2, 5-HT2A, H1, M1, alpha-1) and is uniquely effective for treatment-resistant schizophrenia, but carries risks of agranulocytosis (requires ANC monitoring via REMS program), metabolic syndrome, myocarditis, and seizures. Antidepressant receptor profiles determine both therapeutic effects and side effects: SNRIs (venlafaxine, duloxetine) add norepinephrine reuptake inhibition to serotonin effects, providing dual benefit for depression with comorbid pain; mirtazapine blocks 5-HT2A, 5-HT2C, 5-HT3, alpha-2, and H1 receptors, producing antidepressant, antiemetic, and appetite-stimulating effects with prominent sedation. Bupropion inhibits norepinephrine and dopamine reuptake with no serotonergic activity, making it the antidepressant with the lowest sexual dysfunction risk and a useful adjunct for SSRI-induced sexual side effects." },
